<h2>
    <a href="/blog/the-harmonically-driven-pendulum/">The harmonically-driven pendulum</a>
</h2>




<h6 class="post-meta">
    Posted by:
    
    <a href="/blog/author/christian/">christian</a>
    
    
    
    
    on 25 Jul 2017
</h6>





<a href="/blog/the-harmonically-driven-pendulum/">
    <img class="img-thumbnail pull-left" src="/static/media/uploads/blog/double_pendulum/.thumbnails/_img0073.png/_img0073-90x90.png">
</a>





<p>For the purposes of this article, the harmonically-driven pendulum is one whose anchor point moves in time according to $x_0(t) = A\cos\omega t$. As with <a href="/blog/the-double-pendulum/">previous</a> <a href="/blog/the-spring-pendulum/">posts</a>, the position of the pendulum bob with time can be described using Lagrangian mechanics.
In a coordinate system with the pendulum anchor initially at $(0,0)$ and the $y$-axis pointing up, the components of the bob position and velocity as a function of time are:</p>




